parts:
You are extracting a UBX protocol message definition from u-blox PDF manual pages.

TARGET MESSAGE: UBX-LOG-BATCH
Expected IDs from TOC: class_id=0x21, message_id=0x11

CRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS:
1. Extract ONLY the message named "UBX-LOG-BATCH". Ignore any other messages visible.
2. The payload table shows fields in order. Extract them exactly as shown with correct byte offsets.
3. Verify field sizes match offset differences.

=== DATA TYPES ===

Scalar types (use EXACTLY these values):
- U1, U2, U4, U8 = Unsigned integers (1/2/4/8 bytes)
- I1, I2, I4, I8 = Signed integers - NOTE: "I" is capital letter i, NOT digit 1
- X1, X2, X4, X8 = Bitfields (use for flags, mask, status fields)
- R4, R8 = Floating point (4/8 bytes)
- CH = ASCII character (1 byte)

Array types: Use object format {"array_of": "U1", "count": N}
- Check Type column for "[N]" or "x N" notation
- Verify array size matches offset gap to next field

=== CHARACTER RECOGNITION WARNINGS ===

The PDF uses fonts where these characters look similar:
- "I" (letter i) vs "1" (digit one): Data types are I1, I2, I4 (not 11, 12, 14)
- "O" (letter o) vs "0" (digit zero): Message names like UBX-ODO use letter "O"

=== FIELD EXTRACTION ===

For each field extract:
- name: Exact field name from PDF (preserve camelCase)
- byte_offset: Integer from "Offset" column (0-indexed)
- data_type: UBX type or array object
- description: Field description text
- unit: Physical unit if shown (ms, deg, m/s, etc.)
- scale: If scaling factor shown, include {"raw": "1e-7", "multiplier": 1e-7}
- reserved: Set true for reserved fields
- bitfield: For X-type fields with bit definitions, extract structure

=== ARRAY DETECTION (CRITICAL) ===

Common extraction error: missing arrays. Check carefully:
- Type column shows: "U1[6]", "U1 x 6", "CH[30]" = array
- Offset gaps reveal arrays: offset 4 to 8 with U1 = 4-byte array
- Reserved fields often span multiple bytes

=== BITFIELD DETECTION (CRITICAL) ===

Use X1/X2/X4 (NOT U1/U2/U4) when:
- Field named "flags", "mask", "status", "cfg", "supported", "enabled"
- Description mentions "bitfield" or lists bit meanings
- Sub-table shows bit positions

Extract bitfield structure for ALL X-type fields:
{"bits": [{"name": "bitName", "bit_start": 0, "bit_end": 0, "description": "..."}]}

=== PAYLOAD LENGTH ===

- Fixed: {"fixed": 28}
- Variable: {"variable": {"base": 8, "formula": "8 + N*12", "min": 8}}

=== REPEATED GROUPS (CRITICAL) ===

Many UBX messages contain repeated blocks of fields. Look for:
- "N x ..." or "numXxx x ..." patterns in the payload table
- Fields that repeat based on a count field (e.g., numSvs, numCh)
- Variable-length payloads with repeating structures

Extract repeated groups as:
{"repeated_groups": [{
  "name": "groupName",
  "repetition_type": "count_field",
  "count_field": "numSvs",
  "group_size_bytes": 12,
  "base_offset": 8,
  "fields": [...]
}]}

Common patterns:
- INF messages: Have a "str" repeated group for variable-length text
- NAV-SAT, NAV-ORB: Have satellite blocks repeated per numSvs
- MON-RXBUF: Has pending[] arrays per port

=== MESSAGE TYPE ===

Determine from context:
- "periodic" or "periodic_polled": Output messages sent automatically or on poll
- "input": Messages sent TO the receiver
- "output": Messages sent FROM the receiver  
- "command": One-shot commands
- "get"/"set"/"get_set": Configuration messages
- "poll_request": Poll request (usually empty payload)

=== SPECIAL MESSAGE TYPES ===

**UBX-INF-* (INF-DEBUG, INF-ERROR, INF-NOTICE, INF-WARNING, INF-TEST):**
- These contain a variable-length ASCII string payload
- Extract a single field named "str" with data_type {"array_of": "CH", "count": "variable"}
- Use repeated_groups with repetition_type "fill_remaining" for the string
- Do NOT return empty fields array

**UBX-MGA-* (Multiple GNSS Assistance):**
- Often have MULTIPLE SUB-TYPES on same pages (EPH, ALM, IONO, etc.)
- Each sub-type has different "type" field value and different payload
- Extract ONLY the sub-type matching the message name
- If name includes sub-type (e.g., "UBX-MGA-GPS-EPH"), extract only that

**UBX-LOG-FINDTIME:**
- Has TWO structures: INPUT (request) and OUTPUT (response)
- INPUT: version, type, year, month, day, hour, minute, second, reserved
- OUTPUT: version, type, reserved, entryNumber
- Extract based on message name suffix (-INPUT or -OUTPUT)

**UBX-RXM-RLM:**
- Has SHORT (16 bytes, type=0x01) and LONG (28 bytes, type=0x02) variants
- Extract based on message name suffix (-SHORT or -LONG)

**UBX-RXM-PMREQ:**
- V0 (8 bytes): duration, flags - NO version field
- V1 (16 bytes): version, reserved0[3], duration, flags, wakeupSources
- Extract based on suffix (-V0 or -V1)

=== QUALITY CHECKS ===

Before returning, verify:
- Byte offsets are sequential and non-overlapping
- Field sizes match offset gaps (offset 4 to 8 = 4 bytes)
- Total field sizes match payload length
- All fields from the payload table are included
If any of these appear to fail, you should review your initial extraction and re-extract the message.



=== MESSAGE NAME FORMAT (CRITICAL) ===

The "name" field MUST be EXACTLY "UBX-LOG-BATCH" with NO modifications:
- Do NOT add descriptions like "(Poll request)" or "(Version 0)"
- Do NOT add suffixes like "Request" or "Poll"
- Do NOT include any parenthetical text
- Use ONLY the canonical message name: "UBX-LOG-BATCH"

=== OUTPUT FORMAT ===

Return a JSON object with this structure:
{
  "name": "UBX-LOG-BATCH",
  "class_id": "0xNN",
  "message_id": "0xNN",
  "description": "Short description",
  "message_type": "output",
  "payload": {
    "length": {"fixed": N} or {"variable": {...}},
    "fields": [
      {
        "name": "fieldName",
        "byte_offset": 0,
        "data_type": "U4",
        "description": "...",
        "unit": "ms",
        "scale": {"raw": "1e-7", "multiplier": 1e-7},
        "bitfield": {"bits": [...]}
      }
    ],
    "repeated_groups": [...]
  }
}

Extract the message completely and accurately.

  "reasoning": "My original extraction precisely matches the provided PDF screenshots for the UBX-M10 SPG 5.10 manual. Specifically, I maintained the correct casing for fields such as 'extraOdo' (bit 1 of contentValid), 'hMSL', and 'pDOP', whereas the consensus structure and other manual extractions often normalize these to all-lowercase or all-uppercase. I also correctly captured the bitfield positions for 'psmState' (bits 4..2) and 'valid' (bits 0 and 1), verifying that the field 'valid' has a different bit layout in M10 (bit 0=validDate) compared to some earlier generations like M8 (bit 0=validTime). The payload length of 100 bytes and all byte offsets were calculated and verified against the field sizes.",

  "change_details": null
}

extracted_structure.name: UBX-LOG-BATCH
extracted_structure.description: This message combines position, velocity and time solution, including accuracy figures. The output of this message can be requested via UBX-LOG-RETRIEVEBATCH.

bits.name: extraPvt
bits.description: Extra PVT information is valid. The fields iTOW, tAcc, numSV, HMSL, vAcc, velN, velE, velD, sAcc, headAcc and PDOP are only valid if this flag is set.

bits.name: extraOdo
bits.description: Odometer data is valid. The fields distance, totalDistance and distanceStd are only valid if this flag is set. Note: the odometer feature itself must also be enabled.

fields.name: msgCnt
fields.description: Message counter; increments for each sent UBX-LOG-BATCH message.

fields.name: iTOW
fields.description: GPS time of week of the navigation epoch. See section Clocks and time in the integration manual for description of navigation epoch and iTOW. Only valid if extraPvt is set.

bits.name: validDate
bits.description: 1 = valid UTC Date (see section Time validity in the integration manual for details)

bits.name: validTime
bits.description: 1 = valid UTC Time of Day (see section Time validity in the integration manual for details)

fields.name: tAcc
fields.description: Time accuracy estimate (UTC). Only valid if extraPvt is set.

bits.name: gnssFixOK
bits.description: 1 = valid fix (i.e within DOP & accuracy masks)

bits.name: psmState
bits.description: Power save mode state (see section Power management in the integration manual for details): 0 = PSM is not active, 1 = Enabled (an intermediate state before Acquisition state), 2 = Acquisition, 3 = Tracking, 4 = Power optimized tracking, 5 = Inactive

fields.name: numSV
fields.description: Number of satellites used in Nav Solution. Only valid if extraPvt is set.

fields.name: hMSL
fields.description: Height above mean sea level. Only valid if extraPvt is set.

fields.name: vAcc
fields.description: Vertical accuracy estimate. Only valid if extraPvt is set.

fields.name: velN
fields.description: NED north velocity. Only valid if extraPvt is set.

fields.name: velE
fields.description: NED east velocity. Only valid if extraPvt is set.

fields.name: velD
fields.description: NED down velocity. Only valid if extraPvt is set.

fields.name: sAcc
fields.description: Speed accuracy estimate. Only valid if extraPvt is set.

fields.name: headAcc
fields.description: Heading accuracy estimate. Only valid if extraPvt is set.

fields.name: pDOP
fields.description: Position DOP. Only valid if extraPvt is set.

fields.name: distance
fields.description: Ground distance since last reset. Only valid if extraOdo is set.

fields.name: totalDistance
fields.description: Total cumulative ground distance. Only valid if extraOdo is set.

fields.name: distanceStd
fields.description: Ground distance accuracy (1-sigma). Only valid if extraOdo is set.

review.reasoning: My original extraction precisely matches the provided PDF screenshots for the UBX-M10 SPG 5.10 manual. Specifically, I maintained the correct casing for fields such as 'extraOdo' (bit 1 of contentValid), 'hMSL', and 'pDOP', whereas the consensus structure and other manual extractions often normalize these to all-lowercase or all-uppercase. I also correctly captured the bitfield positions for 'psmState' (bits 4..2) and 'valid' (bits 0 and 1), verifying that the field 'valid' has a different bit layout in M10 (bit 0=validDate) compared to some earlier generations like M8 (bit 0=validTime). The payload length of 100 bytes and all byte offsets were calculated and verified against the field sizes.
